        Official Singles Chart on 6/12/2019

        6 December 2019 - 12 December 2019

        The Official UK Singles Chart reflects the UKs biggest songs of the week, based on audio and video streams, downloads, CDs and vinyl, compiled by the Official Charts Company. The UK Top 40 is broadcast on BBC Radio 1 and MTV, the Top 100 is published exclusively on OfficialCharts.com. View the biggest songs of 2024 so far.

        It stands for "Accelerated Chart Ratio".

        It means that if a song has been on the chart for at least 10 weeks & declined more than the rest of the singles market for three consecutive weeks, the value of its streams are halved.

        One time, there was a tourist attraction called Madame Tussauds Rock Circus in Picadilly Square London. It opened in August 1989 and closed compeletely in September 2001. The Museum was a walkthrough attractions with each room showing artists from a certain decade. The attraction started from the 1950s to the then present day in which case the 1990s. If Madame Tussauds Rock Circus was still open today, there would be a 2000's section and a 2010's section.

        I review everything hot inside and bubbling just under the UK's official top 40 - and as the Christmas songs begin their annual chart takeover, we still have a couple of releases managing to pop their heads out and shine inside the top 40 - one of which, doing so quite unusually! Let's get started.

        (NEW ENTRIES) #10 + #12: THE WEEKND - HEARTLESS // BLINDING LIGHTS
        I'm combining these into one, because I've mostly the same things to say about them. The Weeknd is incredibly hit-or-miss with me, it's actually insane - I've loved upbeat tracks of his like "Starboy" and downbeat ones like "Call Out My Name", but something like "Can't Feel My Face" was largely forgettable and at a certain point, a bit annoying. Now with "Heartless", there's some pretty interesting production going on, and I love how it and the lyrical content alternate throughout the song between the life of partying, drugs and alcohol; and the sadness that comes with that. Despite the track not being convincing enough, however, it's the better out of the two for me: "Blinding Lights" is a promotional song for a Mercedes commercial, and while the beat with this one is certainly much more intriguing, there's not much else that captures me at all - "Heartless" had at least some heartfelt delivery, this one doesn't really! I wanted to give these a joint score, because I feel mostly the same about them, but I really can't: so I'm giving "Heartless" a light 6/10, and "Blinding Lights" a pretty strong 5/10.

        (NEW ENTRY) #14: ELLIE GOULDING - RIVER
        So this track has managed to break into the top 40, being available exclusively on Amazon - and did so with a very good peak! Turns out, it was last year, and the track was once again only available on Amazon Music! Katy Perry's 'Cozy Little Christmas' managed to sneak to a #23 peak last year, so it appears this year they're trying the same strategy to attempt to convert people to their streaming platform.         My thoughts & observations on the UK chart as always

        Dance Monkey by Tones & I extends its singles chart reign to a 10th consecutive week at #1! In doing so, it ties an Official Chart record alongside I Will Always Love You by Whitney Houston from 1992 & Umbrella by Rihanna ft Jay-Z in 2007, that being the longest running #1 of all-time by a female artist!

        Commercially, Dance Monkey racked up 75,000 chart sales for the tracking week, which includes 9.39 million streams.

        Weve gone from one Christmas song inside the Top 40 last week to nine this week! Thats almost a quarter of the entire chart, with still three more charts to go before festive classics have their biggest impact.

        Dont Start Now by Dua Lipa retains the top spot on the national airplay chart!

        Dance Monkey also continues its dominant run on YouTube, where its spending an eighth consecutive week at #1! Compared to last week, it increased 5% in views to 4.6 million over the past seven days.

        THE WEEKND - HEARTLESS (#10)
        While The Weeknds always been hit-or-miss for me, Ive always been able to see his appeal as an R&B singer, since he has a voice thats very distinct on the radio; you know its him straight away! As for this, it certainly falls more on the positive side of things, although I still have my reservations. Of course, I still love the vocal display here, which with how they alternate between a huskier deep tone to the passionate falsetto, almost reminds me of Michael Jackson & while the trap beat here might be very predictable & overused, its the kind of vibe that suits The Weeknd almost better than any other act in the charts right now! That said, where I cant get on board with this so much is in the content, where he discusses how fame made him heartless, which makes you think this would be a sadder vibe from him, but instead he seems to take up almost all the airtime bragging about girls, but also being very disrespectful to them! I mean, the lyrics , but everything else seems to work fine. So for that, solid 6/10!

        THE WEEKND - BLINDING LIGHTS (#12)
        Now, this is more like it! I definitely meant the MJ comparison in the Heartless review above as a compliment, but with The Weeknd now taking on brighter & groovier vocals, this might actually be an even better fit for him! Ive also always loved whenever The Weeknd goes into a disco-funk throwback (such as when he collaborated with Daft Punk on Starboy & I Feel It Coming), which is why the synth-driven electro-pop sparkle is a standout here; it might pack less of a punch than its companion single, but its a heck of a lot more fun! See, this is a much more effective approach on how to get a lover, because its really impressive! This mightve been the lower of the two debuts for The Weeknd, but it certainly has more hit potential. As such, strong 8/10!

        ELLIE GOULDING - RIVER (#14)
        Yeah, were not only getting Christmas songs re-enter, but therell also be a lot of debuts here & there as we approach the 25th! As for this, its particularly interesting to see it this high, since it was an Amazon Music exclusive up until literally a few days ago. Its also a cover of the 1971 classic by Joni Mitchell & on top of that, its actually really enjoyable! Its honestly reminiscent of her early days where she covered the classic Your Song for the John Lewis Christmas Advert for example, especially with the rich vocal delivery & her cooing upper register, which is primarily a piano-driven ballad! What I respect a lot more coming from Ellie is how she can carry the descriptive details so well in her singing, which allows this to resonate on a very strong level, even when like me, youve only heard it for the first time! I do wish we got a bit more on the ending, but thats something I feel couldve been improved on the original anyway. Regardless, I still think this is such a sweet remake of the original, so Im giving it a solid 8/10!

        TREVOR DANIEL - FALLING (#40)
        Looks like we have another TikTok entry sneaking its way in despite all the Christmas songs & while Ive never got on board with a majority of songs getting big from this platform, trap singers have been growing on me a lot throughout 2019, but not enough for me to get on board with this, because its honestly nothing youll care about! Seriously, weve heard Post Malone do this sort of thing about a year or two ago, except with production thats nowhere near as cheap as it is here! He even sounds like a less convincing version of Post Malone too, especially when you only have a single verse & a hook that doesnt even any attempt to rhyme. I mean, the low-end rumbles of the synths along with the watery guitars mightve developed a bit of an atmosphere at points here, but even then, theyre fairly short-lived! Even the content doesnt go into any sort of detail thats worth a lot of discussion, so yeah, its chances of becoming a hit with any sort of staying power are extremely unlikely, especially when December has more competition than ever in the build-up to Christmas! Honestly, Ill stick with those festive classics, not something with this much mediocrity. For me, light 4/10!

        On the albums chart, its a lucky 13 for Robbie Williams, as he scores his 13th #1 studio album with The Christmas Present, tying Elvis Presleys record for the most #1 albums ever by a solo artist!

        The rest of the Top 5 is: Youre In My Heart by Rod Stewart & The Royal Philharmonic Orchestra (3-2), Everyday Life by Coldplay (1-3), Divinely Uninspired To A Hellish Extent by Lewis Capaldi (stationary at #4) & Back Together by Michael Ball & Alfie Boe (stationary at #5).

        Looking ahead to next week, these songs could enter the Top 40 for the first time: Christmas Tree Farm by Taylor Swift, Adore You by Harry Styles, a couple of tracks from Romance by Camila Cabello, a couple other new Christmas songs & maybe even more.

        Ill also be posting my Top 100 Songs Of 2019 on this thread a little later this evening!

        Thanks for reading everyone! I hope you all have a good weekend. :)
